Model Adjustments and Quality

Pseudo \(R^2\): For similar models, the higher the Pseudo \(R^2\), the better the model fit;
Akaike’s Information Criterion (AIC): For similar models, the lower the AIC, the better the model fit;
Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC): For similar models, the lower the BIC, the better the model fit;

Seasonality Without Trend

Recall that dummy variables can be used to deal with categorical independent variables in a multiple regression model.
We will treat the season as a categorical variable.
Recall that when a categorical variable has \(k\) levels, \(k - 1\) dummy variables are required.
If there are four seasons, we have the following dummy variables:



\[
\text{Qtr1} =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if Quarter 1} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\quad
\text{Qtr2} =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if Quarter 2} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\quad
\text{Qtr3} =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if Quarter 3} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\quad
\text{Qtr4} =
\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if Quarter 4} \\
0 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

Interpretation of Results: Log-Odds

For a one-unit increase in gre, the log-odds of the dependent variable (admit) increase by 0.002;
For a one-unit increase in gpa, the log-odds of the DV increase by 0.804;
In the case of the variable rank, being a graduate of an institution with rank\(=2\) changes the log-odds by \(-0.675\) compared to an institution with rank\(=1\).

 Source: How do I interpret Odds Ratios in Logistic Regression?

